<!-- Description Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> element is VB's configuration surface. It controls document metadata, theming, performance hints, social sharing, and service worker opt-in. VB's <code>partials/head.njk</code> template generates the full <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> from frontmatter variables, so most pages only need to set <code>title</code>, <code>description</code>, and optionally <code>image</code> in their YAML front matter.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Basic Example Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Basic Example</h2>
    <h3>Minimal</h3>
    <code-block language="html" label="Minimal head">{{ minimalExample | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Typical VB Page</h3>
    <p>The <code>partials/head.njk</code> template generates this structure automatically:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Full VB head output">{{ typicalExample | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <!-- Required Elements Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Required Elements</h2>
    <p>Every VB page must include these elements. The head partial handles all of them automatically.</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Character encoding. Must appear within the first 1024 bytes of the document.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;meta name="viewport" ...&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Viewport configuration for responsive layout. VB sets <code>width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0</code>.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark"&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Tells the browser the page supports both color schemes before CSS loads. Prevents a white flash for dark-mode users and enables correct form control styling.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;title&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Page title. VB concatenates as <code>Page Title | Site Name</code>, or just the site name if no page title is set.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;meta name="description"&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Page description for search engines and social previews. Set via the <code>description</code> frontmatter field.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- Favicon Strategy Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Favicon Strategy</h2>
    <p>VB uses a three-tier favicon approach for maximum browser coverage:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Favicon links">{{ faviconExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>File</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>favicon.svg</code></td>
          <td>Primary. Scales perfectly, supports <code>prefers-color-scheme</code> media queries for dark-mode favicons.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>favicon-32x32.png</code></td>
          <td>Fallback for browsers that don't support SVG favicons (older Safari, some RSS readers).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>apple-touch-icon.png</code></td>
          <td>180&times;180 PNG used when iOS users add the site to their home screen.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- Social Metadata Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Social Metadata</h2>
    <p>VB generates Open Graph and Twitter Card tags automatically from frontmatter.</p>

    <h3>Open Graph</h3>
    <code-block language="html" label="Open Graph tags">{{ ogExample | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Twitter Card</h3>
    <code-block language="html" label="Twitter Card tags">{{ twitterExample | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Custom OG Image</h3>
    <p>Override the default <code>/og-image.png</code> with the <code>image</code> frontmatter field:</p>
    <code-block language="yaml" label="Frontmatter with custom OG image">{{ ogFrontmatterExample | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <!-- Canonical URL Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Canonical URL</h2>
    <p>VB auto-generates a canonical URL from <code>site.url</code> + <code>page.url</code>. This tells search engines the preferred URL for each page, preventing duplicate content issues.</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Canonical link">{{ canonicalExample | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <!-- Theme Flash Prevention Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Theme Flash Prevention</h2>
    <p>An inline <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> runs before CSS loads to prevent a flash of wrong theme. It reads the user's saved preferences from <code>localStorage</code> and applies data attributes to <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> synchronously:</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Preference</th>
          <th>Storage Key</th>
          <th>Attribute Set</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Light/dark mode</td>
          <td><code>vb-theme</code> → <code>.mode</code></td>
          <td><code>data-mode</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Brand theme</td>
          <td><code>vb-theme</code> → <code>.brand</code></td>
          <td rowspan="2"><code>data-theme</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Accessibility themes</td>
          <td><code>vb-a11y-themes</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Fluid scaling preset</td>
          <td><code>vb-theme</code> → <code>.fluid</code></td>
          <td><code>data-fluid</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Reduced motion</td>
          <td><code>vb-extensions</code> → <code>.motionFx</code></td>
          <td><code>data-motion-reduced</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Browser chrome color</td>
          <td><em>(derived from mode)</em></td>
          <td><code>&lt;meta name="theme-color"&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>The script also updates the <code>theme-color</code> meta tag so the browser chrome matches the applied mode rather than the OS preference.</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Theme flash prevention script">{{ themeFlashExample | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <!-- Performance Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Performance</h2>

    <h3>Preconnect</h3>
    <p>VB preconnects to Google Fonts so the DNS lookup, TCP handshake, and TLS negotiation happen in parallel with CSS parsing:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Font preconnect">{{ preconnectExample | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Theme Color</h3>
    <p>Two <code>&lt;meta name="theme-color"&gt;</code> tags tell the browser what color to paint the address bar and tab strip, matched to VB's default backgrounds:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Theme color meta tags">{{ themeColorExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>The theme flash prevention script dynamically updates these to match the user's chosen mode, so the browser chrome stays in sync even when the mode is explicitly set (not following OS preference).</p>

    <h3>CSS Loading</h3>
    <p>VB uses different CSS paths in development and production:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Development CSS">{{ cssDevExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" label="Production CSS">{{ cssProdExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>The <code>site.css</code> data variable handles this automatically — <code>/src/main.css</code> in dev mode (served by Caddy), <code>/cdn/vanilla-breeze.css</code> in production.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Service Worker Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Service Worker</h2>
    <p>VB's service worker is opt-in. Add the meta tag to enable offline caching and background updates:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Service worker opt-in">{{ swExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>Alternatively, set the flag in JavaScript before VB's autoloader runs:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="JavaScript opt-in">{{ swJsExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>When enabled, VB registers a service worker that caches CSS, JS, and font assets using a stale-while-revalidate strategy. See the <a href="/docs/performance/">Performance page</a> for details on cache strategies and lifecycle.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Extension Point Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Extension Point</h2>
    <p>Child layouts can inject additional content into <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> using the <code>extraHead</code> block. This is the recommended way to add page-specific styles, fonts, or scripts:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Using the extraHead block">{{ extraHeadExample | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>The block appears after all standard head content, so page-specific styles can override defaults without specificity battles.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Permitted Child Elements Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Permitted Child Elements</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> element may only contain metadata content:</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;title&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Document title (exactly one required)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;meta&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Metadata: charset, viewport, description, theme-color, etc.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;link&gt;</code></td>
          <td>External resources: stylesheets, favicons, preconnects, canonical URLs</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;style&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Inline CSS (prefer external stylesheets; use for critical CSS or page-specific overrides)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;script&gt;</code></td>
          <td>JavaScript (VB uses this for theme flash prevention)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;base&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Base URL for relative links (rarely needed)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;noscript&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Fallback content when JavaScript is disabled</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- Accessibility Section -->
  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>lang</code> on <code>&lt;html&gt;</code>:</strong> Set on the parent <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element (not <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>), this attribute tells screen readers which pronunciation rules to use. VB's base layout sets <code>lang="en"</code> by default.</li>
      <li><strong><code>description</code> meta:</strong> Provides a concise page summary for search engines and assistive technology. Screen readers can announce this to help users decide whether to continue reading.</li>
      <li><strong><code>color-scheme</code> meta:</strong> Informs the browser about supported color schemes before CSS loads. This is essential for <code>forced-colors</code> mode and ensures native form controls (inputs, selects, textareas) render in the correct scheme from the first paint.</li>
      <li><strong>Title pattern:</strong> The <code>Page Title | Site Name</code> format gives screen reader users immediate context about both the specific page and the site they're on.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

